   <text>
      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Richmond ¶ Nov 2nd 1881 ¶ My dear Baron ¶  ¶ I went to Manly Beach yesterday on purpose to look after  ¶ Macrozamia ¶   ¶ spiralis ¶ . ¶  ¶ It grows about a mile or so from the sea, in a soil of sand ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">81.11.02</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From William Woolls</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M46, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS found with a specimen of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Macrozamia miquelii</seg> (MEL 237352). MS annotation by M: 'Answ 5/11/81'. Letter not found.</p>
               </note>Richmond<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">All places named are in NSW.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Nov 2nd 1881</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Baron</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I went to Manly Beach yesterday on purpose to look after <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Macrozamia</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">spiralis</hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It grows about a mile or so from the sea, in a soil of sand &amp; decomposed vegetable matter amidst some Eucalypts &amp; a variety of shrubs.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>(1) The length of the leaf-stalk in full grown plants is five or six feet, &amp; the number of leaflets 60 pairs!<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">A sample leaf was inserted into the letter at this point, but has since been removed.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>(2) The lower leaflets always shorten gradually, &amp; the lowest ones are reduced to sharp thorns.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>(3) There is no wool either on the stalk or leaves, but the whole plant is glabrous.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>(4) The stems rise 15 or 18 inches above the ground, being about a foot in diameter. (the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">small plant</hi>
               </seg> has the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">caudex</hi>
               </seg> underground)</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>(5) The lowest leaves (those last formed?) are about two feet.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>(6) The apex of the leaflets is mucronate.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>(7) The peduncle of the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">male</hi>
               </seg> cone is a foot or more, the cone itself 9 or 10 inches long &amp; from 6 to 8 inches round, the scales ¾ of an inch broad with turned up cuneiform, pungent points</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was not so fortunate as to find a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">female cone</hi>
               </seg>, but I picked up a few nuts. I am afraid the cones will not be ripe before autumn, but a friend has promised to examine the plants at Randwick.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">M. spiralis</hi>
               </seg> occurs near the coast from Port Jackson (or perhaps more northward) to Twofold Bay</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It differs from the other species in not having the leaflets <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">ever</hi>
               </seg> toothed, &amp; in having a flat instead of a terete rachis: being also smooth.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I noticed a few plants of the dwarf species growing amongst the others. The young leaflets were toothed at the apex. The leaf stalks are woolly at the base.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The female cone in <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">M. spiralis</hi>
               </seg> is larger than D.C states,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">A de Candolle (1868), p. 535.</p>
               </note> &amp; the leaves more numerous. In some, there are 60 pairs, whilst in the dwarf ones, they seldom are more than 30 or 40, though in one I counted 45.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have two plants of the small one near at hand, but I do not think the cones will be ready before Xmas. They are smaller than those of the true M. spiralis.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I send you by post the following:</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No. (1) Three pieces of a leaf of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">M. spiralis</hi>
               </seg> which had 60 pairs of leaflets. The three pieces are from the top, the middle, &amp; the base.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No. (2) A new or young frond.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No. (3) Leaves &amp;c of the small <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Macrozamia</hi>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In the other parcel are some scales of the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">male</hi>
               </seg> cone of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">M. spiralis</hi>
               </seg> &amp; a few nuts of the same from a female plant. They are last years &amp; have shrunk.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours very sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>W. Woolls<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">A herbarium label is filed with the letter, marked by M: 'Macrozamia miquelii. From the coast to the Blue Mountains, in the litoral tract occasionally mixed with M. spiralis. 1881. Woolls'.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron Mueller</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Macrozamia%20spiralis">Macrozamia spiralis</name>
            </p>
         </div>
      </body>
